{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-help-file-corrupted-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">&ldquo;File corrupted&rdquo; / data damage, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A QuickBooks company file (the <em>.QBW</em>) stores every transaction, list, and balance in one structured database. &ldquo;Corruption&rdquo; or &ldquo;data damage&rdquo; means that structure has developed internal inconsistencies &mdash; the records no longer agree with one another the way they should. You usually notice it as a cluster of symptoms: Verify Data reporting problems; account balances that don&rsquo;t add up; transactions that disappear, change, or won&rsquo;t open; reports that no longer tie; or the file crashing and behaving erratically.</p>
      <p>The good news is that most damage traces to a short list of causes, and the self-fix steps below address them in order &mdash; backing up first, then running Verify Data and Rebuild Data, then QuickBooks Tool Hub and File Doctor clears a large share of cases. What the steps <em>can&rsquo;t</em> always fix is deeper damage: transaction or list corruption a rebuild can&rsquo;t resolve, a file that has outgrown its limits, or damage that has compounded over time. That part is a recovery and cleanup job, not a one-click utility &mdash; and if the underlying issue is your Intuit account or login, that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve, not something we can reach.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

